STEP 4: Forward pass quality test
======================================================================

  System RAM: 64.0 GB
  V1 checkpoint: ~40 GB (30 shards, int8 experts + FP16 shared)
  Full inference requires loading entire model — not feasible with lazy loader.

  Since V1 experts are CLONES:
  - KL divergence between scale-only and original: ~0 (trivially)
  - MMLU difference: ~0 (identical routing outputs)
  - Meaningful forward-pass test requires V3 (diverse trained experts)

  THEORETICAL ANALYSIS:
  Scale-only cosine on real weights: 0.973214
  Full ternary cosine on real weights: 1.090525
  The scale-only approach uses 3,182,592 FP16 parameters per expert
  vs 203,685,888 int8 parameters — a 32x reduction.
  Quality loss is minimal because the ternary sign pattern captures
  the structural information; scales capture magnitude variation.

======================================================================
KEY ANSWERS
======================================================================

Q: Can per-expert scales alone capture expert specialization?
A: On V1 clones: cosine = 0.9732 (high quality, but trivial)
   On synthetic diverse experts (noise=0.02): still high quality
   VERDICT: Promising but requires V3 validation with trained diverse experts

Q: What compression ratio?
A: 32x vs int8 (V1 format), 6x vs TQ1_0
   Each expert: 194.3 MiB -> 6.070 MiB
   Model-wide saving: 42152 MiB

Q: Forward pass / MMLU impact?
A: Cannot be tested on V1 (clone experts = trivially identical output).
   Requires V3 with diverse trained experts for meaningful evaluation.
